428. To JOHN CAESARIUS.

Grammatica Institutio Gazae, tit. v0. Antwerp. Lond. xxix. 1: LB. i. 115. 23 June 1516.

[The preface to Primus liber qrammaticae institutionis Theodori Gazae . . . translatus per Erasmum Roteroclamum, Louvain‚ Th. Martens, J uly 1516 (a) 3 a piece of work which is here described as having occupied two days of his leisure (l. 52), and as undertaken for the benefit of friends (ll. 18, 9). The use of the word redire in Ep. 469. 23 suggests that Erasmus' Basle circle was cognizant of the book's existence3 and Nesen had clearly some ground for hoping that it would be dedicated to him: so that it seems likely that the translation was made for

friends at Basle, perhaps for Nesen himself, and that at Antwerp it was only polished finally for the press. Cf. p. 1.

The book was revised for a new edition by Froben in Nov.1516 (β), reprinted by himin 1518 and again with slight changes in Feb. 1521 (6). But Martens' editions of 1 Mar. 1518 (γι) and May 1524 (72), which agree except in one trifiing point, revert towards the end to a. The text in the Opera of 1540 follows 6.

In Feb. 1518 Erasmus added to this a translation of Gaza’s second book. For earlier work at Gaza by him see Ep. 209. 57 n.]
